rdfs:label: Event
dc:description: Something that happens at a given time and (typically) place. Elements of this tag subtree designate the general category in which an event falls.
omn:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (suggestedTag some Task-property) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema)
owm:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (suggestedTag some Task-property) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema

rdfs:label: Sensory-event
dc:description: Something perceivable by the participant. An event meant to be an experimental stimulus should include the tag Task-property/Task-event-role/Experimental-stimulus.
omn:EquivalentTo: Event and (suggestedTag some Task-event-role) and (suggestedTag some Sensory-presentation)
owm:EquivalentTo: Event and (suggestedTag some Task-event-role) and (suggestedTag some Sensory-presentation)

rdfs:label: Agent-action
dc:description: Any action engaged in by an agent (see the Agent subtree for agent categories). A participant response to an experiment stimulus should include the tag Agent-property/Agent-task-role/Experiment-participant.
omn:EquivalentTo: Event and (suggestedTag some Task-event-role) and (suggestedTag some Agent)
owm:EquivalentTo: Event and (suggestedTag some Task-event-role) and (suggestedTag some Agent)

rdfs:label: Data-feature
dc:description: An event marking the occurrence of a data feature such as an interictal spike or alpha burst that is often added post hoc to the data record.

rdfs:label: Experiment-control
dc:description: An event pertaining to the physical control of the experiment during its operation.

rdfs:label: Experiment-procedure
dc:description: An event indicating an experimental procedure, as in performing a saliva swab during the experiment or administering a survey.

rdfs:label: Experiment-structure
dc:description: An event specifying a change-point of the structure of experiment. This event is typically used to indicate a change in experimental conditions or tasks.

rdfs:label: Measurement-event
dc:description: A discrete measure returned by an instrument.

rdfs:label: Agent
dc:description: Someone or something that takes an active role or produces a specified effect.The role or effect may be implicit. Being alive or performing an activity such as a computation may qualify something to be an agent. An agent may also be something that simulates something else.
omn:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (suggestedTag some Agent-property) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema)
owm:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (suggestedTag some Agent-property) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema

rdfs:label: Animal-agent
dc:description: An agent that is an animal.

rdfs:label: Avatar-agent
dc:description: An agent associated with an icon or avatar representing another agent.

rdfs:label: Controller-agent
dc:description: Experiment control software or hardware.

rdfs:label: Human-agent
dc:description: A person who takes an active role or produces a specified effect.

rdfs:label: Robotic-agent
dc:description: An agent mechanical device capable of performing a variety of often complex tasks on command or by being programmed in advance.

rdfs:label: Software-agent
dc:description: An agent computer program that interacts with the participant in an active role such as an AI advisor.

rdfs:label: Action
dc:description: Do something.
omn:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema)
owm:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema

rdfs:label: Communicate
dc:description: Action conveying knowledge of or about something.

rdfs:label: Communicate-gesturally
dc:description: Communicate nonverbally using visible bodily actions, either in place of speech or together and in parallel with spoken words. Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-upper-extremity)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-upper-extremity)

rdfs:label: Clap-hands
dc:description: Strike the palms of against one another resoundingly, and usually repeatedly, especially to express approval.

rdfs:label: Clear-throat
dc:description: Cough slightly so as to speak more clearly, attract attention, or to express hesitancy before saying something awkward.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-head)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-head)

rdfs:label: Frown
dc:description: Express disapproval, displeasure, or concentration, typically by turning down the corners of the mouth.

rdfs:label: Grimace
dc:description: Make a twisted expression, typically expressing disgust, pain, or wry amusement.

rdfs:label: Nod-head
dc:description: Tilt head in alternating up and down arcs along the sagittal plane. It is most commonly, but not universally, used to indicate agreement, acceptance, or acknowledgement.

rdfs:label: Pump-fist
dc:description: Raise with fist clenched in triumph or affirmation.

rdfs:label: Raise-eyebrows
dc:description: Move eyebrows upward.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)

rdfs:label: Shake-fist
dc:description: Clench hand into a fist and shake to demonstrate anger.

rdfs:label: Shake-head
dc:description: Turn head from side to side as a way of showing disagreement or refusal.

rdfs:label: Shhh
dc:description: Place finger over lips and possibly uttering the syllable shhh to indicate the need to be quiet.

rdfs:label: Shrug
dc:description: Lift shoulders up towards head to indicate a lack of knowledge about a particular topic.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-upper-extremity) and (relatedTag some Move-torso)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-upper-extremity) and (relatedTag some Move-torso)

rdfs:label: Smile
dc:description: Form facial features into a pleased, kind, or amused expression, typically with the corners of the mouth turned up and the front teeth exposed.

rdfs:label: Spread-hands
dc:description: Spread hands apart to indicate ignorance.

rdfs:label: Thumb-up
dc:description: Extend the thumb upward to indicate approval.

rdfs:label: Thumbs-down
dc:description: Extend the thumb downward to indicate disapproval.

rdfs:label: Wave
dc:description: Raise hand and move left and right, as a greeting or sign of departure.

rdfs:label: Widen-eyes
dc:description: Open eyes and possibly with eyebrows lifted especially to express surprise or fear.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)

rdfs:label: Wink
dc:description: Close and open one eye quickly, typically to indicate that something is a joke or a secret or as a signal of affection or greeting.
omn:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)
owm:EquivalentTo: Communicate-gesturally and (relatedTag some Move-face) and (relatedTag some Move-eyes)

rdfs:label: Communicate-musically
dc:description: Communicate using music.

rdfs:label: Hum
dc:description: Make a low, steady continuous sound like that of a bee. Sing with the lips closed and without uttering speech.

rdfs:label: Play-instrument
dc:description: Make musical sounds using an instrument.

rdfs:label: Sing
dc:description: Produce musical tones by means of the voice.

rdfs:label: Vocalize
dc:description: Utter vocal sounds.

rdfs:label: Whistle
dc:description: Produce a shrill clear sound by forcing breath out or air in through the puckered lips.

rdfs:label: Communicate-vocally
dc:description: Communicate using mouth or vocal cords.

rdfs:label: Cry
dc:description: Shed tears associated with emotions, usually sadness but also joy or frustration.

rdfs:label: Groan
dc:description: Make a deep inarticulate sound in response to pain or despair.

rdfs:label: Laugh
dc:description: Make the spontaneous sounds and movements of the face and body that are the instinctive expressions of lively amusement and sometimes also of contempt or derision.

rdfs:label: Scream
dc:description: Make loud, vociferous cries or yells to express pain, excitement, or fear.

rdfs:label: Shout
dc:description: Say something very loudly.

rdfs:label: Sigh
dc:description: Emit a long, deep, audible breath expressing sadness, relief, tiredness, or a similar feeling.

rdfs:label: Speak
dc:description: Communicate using spoken language.

rdfs:label: Whisper
dc:description: Speak very softly using breath without vocal cords.

rdfs:label: Move
dc:description: Move in a specified direction or manner. Change position or posture.

rdfs:label: Breathe
dc:description: Inhale or exhale during respiration.

rdfs:label: Blow
dc:description: Expel air through pursed lips.

rdfs:label: Cough
dc:description: Suddenly and audibly expel air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation.

rdfs:label: Exhale
dc:description: Blow out or expel breath.

rdfs:label: Hiccup
dc:description: Involuntarily spasm the diaphragm and respiratory organs, with a sudden closure of the glottis and a characteristic sound like that of a cough.

rdfs:label: Hold-breath
dc:description: Interrupt normal breathing by ceasing to inhale or exhale.

rdfs:label: Inhale
dc:description: Draw in with the breath through the nose or mouth.

rdfs:label: Sneeze
dc:description: Suddenly and violently expel breath through the nose and mouth.

rdfs:label: Sniff
dc:description: Draw in air audibly through the nose to detect a smell, to stop it from running, or to express contempt.

rdfs:label: Move-body
dc:description: Move entire body.

rdfs:label: Bend
dc:description: Move body in a bowed or curved manner.

rdfs:label: Dance
dc:description: Perform a purposefully selected sequences of human movement often with aesthetic or symbolic value. Move rhythmically to music, typically following a set sequence of steps.

rdfs:label: Fall-down
dc:description: Lose balance and collapse.

rdfs:label: Flex
dc:description: Cause a muscle to stand out by contracting or tensing it. Bend a limb or joint.

rdfs:label: Jerk
dc:description: Make a quick, sharp, sudden movement.

rdfs:label: Lie-down
dc:description: Move to a horizontal or resting position.

rdfs:label: Recover-balance
dc:description: Return to a stable, upright body position.

rdfs:label: Shudder
dc:description: Tremble convulsively, sometimes as a result of fear or revulsion.

rdfs:label: Sit-down
dc:description: Move from a standing to a sitting position.

rdfs:label: Sit-up
dc:description: Move from lying down to a sitting position.

rdfs:label: Stand-up
dc:description: Move from a sitting to a standing position.

rdfs:label: Stretch
dc:description: Straighten or extend body or a part of body to its full length, typically so as to tighten muscles or in order to reach something.

rdfs:label: Stumble
dc:description: Trip or momentarily lose balance and almost fall.

rdfs:label: Turn
dc:description: Change or cause to change direction.

rdfs:label: Move-body-part
dc:description: Move one part of a body.

rdfs:label: Move-eyes
dc:description: Move eyes.

rdfs:label: Blink
dc:description: Shut and open the eyes quickly.

rdfs:label: Close-eyes
dc:description: Lower and keep eyelids in a closed position.

rdfs:label: Fixate
dc:description: Direct eyes to a specific point or target.

rdfs:label: Inhibit-blinks
dc:description: Purposely prevent blinking.

rdfs:label: Open-eyes
dc:description: Raise eyelids to expose pupil.

rdfs:label: Saccade
dc:description: Move eyes rapidly between fixation points.

rdfs:label: Squint
dc:description: Squeeze one or both eyes partly closed in an attempt to see more clearly or as a reaction to strong light.

rdfs:label: Stare
dc:description: Look fixedly or vacantly at someone or something with eyes wide open.

rdfs:label: Move-face
dc:description: Move the face or jaw.

rdfs:label: Bite
dc:description: Seize with teeth or jaws an object or organism so as to grip or break the surface covering.

rdfs:label: Burp
dc:description: Noisily release air from the stomach through the mouth. Belch.

rdfs:label: Chew
dc:description: Repeatedly grinding, tearing, and or crushing with teeth or jaws.

rdfs:label: Gurgle
dc:description: Make a hollow bubbling sound like that made by water running out of a bottle.

rdfs:label: Swallow
dc:description: Cause or allow something, especially food or drink to pass down the throat.

rdfs:label: Gulp
dc:description: Swallow quickly or in large mouthfuls, often audibly, sometimes to indicate apprehension.

rdfs:label: Yawn
dc:description: Take a deep involuntary inhalation with the mouth open often as a sign of drowsiness or boredom.

rdfs:label: Move-head
dc:description: Move head.

rdfs:label: Lift-head
dc:description: Tilt head back lifting chin.

rdfs:label: Lower-head
dc:description: Move head downward so that eyes are in a lower position.

rdfs:label: Turn-head
dc:description: Rotate head horizontally to look in a different direction.

rdfs:label: Move-lower-extremity
dc:description: Move leg and/or foot.

rdfs:label: Curl-toes
dc:description: Bend toes sometimes to grip.

rdfs:label: Hop
dc:description: Jump on one foot.

rdfs:label: Jog
dc:description: Run at a trot to exercise.

rdfs:label: Jump
dc:description: Move off the ground or other surface through sudden muscular effort in the legs.

rdfs:label: Kick
dc:description: Strike out or flail with the foot or feet.Strike using the leg, in unison usually with an area of the knee or lower using the foot.

rdfs:label: Pedal
dc:description: Move by working the pedals of a bicycle or other machine.

rdfs:label: Press-foot
dc:description: Move by pressing foot.

rdfs:label: Run
dc:description: Travel on foot at a fast pace.

rdfs:label: Step
dc:description: Put one leg in front of the other and shift weight onto it.

rdfs:label: Heel-strike
dc:description: Strike the ground with the heel during a step.

rdfs:label: Toe-off
dc:description: Push with toe as part of a stride.

rdfs:label: Trot
dc:description: Run at a moderate pace, typically with short steps.

rdfs:label: Walk
dc:description: Move at a regular pace by lifting and setting down each foot in turn never having both feet off the ground at once.

rdfs:label: Move-torso
dc:description: Move body trunk.

rdfs:label: Move-upper-extremity
dc:description: Move arm, shoulder, and/or hand.

rdfs:label: Drop
dc:description: Let or cause to fall vertically.

rdfs:label: Grab
dc:description: Seize suddenly or quickly. Snatch or clutch.

rdfs:label: Grasp
dc:description: Seize and hold firmly.

rdfs:label: Hold-down
dc:description: Prevent someone or something from moving by holding them firmly.

rdfs:label: Lift
dc:description: Raising something to higher position.

rdfs:label: Make-fist
dc:description: Close hand tightly with the fingers bent against the palm.

rdfs:label: Point
dc:description: Draw attention to something by extending a finger or arm.

rdfs:label: Press
dc:description: Apply pressure to something to flatten, shape, smooth or depress it. This action tag should be used to indicate key presses and mouse clicks.

rdfs:label: Push
dc:description: Apply force in order to move something away. Use Press to indicate a key press or mouse click.

rdfs:label: Reach
dc:description: Stretch out your arm in order to get or touch something.

rdfs:label: Release
dc:description: Make available or set free.

rdfs:label: Retract
dc:description: Draw or pull back.

rdfs:label: Scratch
dc:description: Drag claws or nails over a surface or on skin.

rdfs:label: Snap-fingers
dc:description: Make a noise by pushing second finger hard against thumb and then releasing it suddenly so that it hits the base of the thumb.

rdfs:label: Touch
dc:description: Come into or be in contact with.

rdfs:label: Perceive
dc:description: Produce an internal, conscious image through stimulating a sensory system.

rdfs:label: Hear
dc:description: Give attention to a sound.

rdfs:label: See
dc:description: Direct gaze toward someone or something or in a specified direction.

rdfs:label: Sense-by-touch
dc:description: Sense something through receptors in the skin.

rdfs:label: Smell
dc:description: Inhale in order to ascertain an odor or scent.

rdfs:label: Taste
dc:description: Sense a flavor in the mouth and throat on contact with a substance.

rdfs:label: Perform
dc:description: Carry out or accomplish an action, task, or function.

rdfs:label: Close
dc:description: Act as to blocked against entry or passage.

rdfs:label: Collide-with
dc:description: Hit with force when moving.

rdfs:label: Halt
dc:description: Bring or come to an abrupt stop.

rdfs:label: Modify
dc:description: Change something.

rdfs:label: Open
dc:description: Widen an aperture, door, or gap, especially one allowing access to something.

rdfs:label: Operate
dc:description: Control the functioning of a machine, process, or system.

rdfs:label: Play
dc:description: Engage in activity for enjoyment and recreation rather than a serious or practical purpose.

rdfs:label: Read
dc:description: Interpret something that is written or printed.

rdfs:label: Repeat
dc:description: Make do or perform again.

rdfs:label: Rest
dc:description: Be inactive in order to regain strength, health, or energy.

rdfs:label: Ride
dc:description: Ride on an animal or in a vehicle. Ride conveys some notion that another agent has partial or total control of the motion.

rdfs:label: Write
dc:description: Communicate or express by means of letters or symbols written or imprinted on a surface.

rdfs:label: Think
dc:description: Direct the mind toward someone or something or use the mind actively to form connected ideas.

rdfs:label: Allow
dc:description: Allow access to something such as allowing a car to pass.

rdfs:label: Attend-to
dc:description: Focus mental experience on specific targets.

rdfs:label: Count
dc:description: Tally items either silently or aloud.

rdfs:label: Deny
dc:description: Refuse to give or grant something requested or desired by someone.

rdfs:label: Detect
dc:description: Discover or identify the presence or existence of something.

rdfs:label: Discriminate
dc:description: Recognize a distinction.

rdfs:label: Encode
dc:description: Convert information or an instruction into a particular form.

rdfs:label: Evade
dc:description: Escape or avoid, especially by cleverness or trickery.

rdfs:label: Generate
dc:description: Cause something, especially an emotion or situation to arise or come about.

rdfs:label: Identify
dc:description: Establish or indicate who or what someone or something is.

rdfs:label: Imagine
dc:description: Form a mental image or concept of something.

rdfs:label: Judge
dc:description: Evaluate evidence to make a decision or form a belief.

rdfs:label: Learn
dc:description: Adaptively change behavior as the result of experience.

rdfs:label: Memorize
dc:description: Adaptively change behavior as the result of experience.

rdfs:label: Plan
dc:description: Think about the activities required to achieve a desired goal.

rdfs:label: Predict
dc:description: Say or estimate that something will happen or will be a consequence of something without having exact information.

rdfs:label: Recall
dc:description: Remember information by mental effort.

rdfs:label: Recognize
dc:description: Identify someone or something from having encountered them before.

rdfs:label: Respond
dc:description: React to something such as a treatment or a stimulus.

rdfs:label: Switch-attention
dc:description: Transfer attention from one focus to another.

rdfs:label: Track
dc:description: Follow a person, animal, or object through space or time.

rdfs:label: Item
dc:description: An independently existing thing (living or nonliving).
omn:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema)
owm:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema

rdfs:label: Biological-item
dc:description: An entity that is biological, that is related to living organisms.

rdfs:label: Anatomical-item
dc:description: A biological structure, system, fluid or other substance excluding single molecular entities.

rdfs:label: Body
dc:description: The biological structure representing an organism.

rdfs:label: Body-part
dc:description: Any part of an organism.

rdfs:label: Head
dc:description: The upper part of the human body, or the front or upper part of the body of an animal, typically separated from the rest of the body by a neck, and containing the brain, mouth, and sense organs.

rdfs:label: Head-part
dc:description: A part of the head.

rdfs:label: Brain
dc:description: Organ inside the head that is made up of nerve cells and controls the body.

rdfs:label: Brain-region
dc:description: A region of the brain.

rdfs:label: Cerebellum
dc:description: A major structure of the brain located near the brainstem. It plays a key role in motor control, coordination, precision, with contributions to different cognitive functions.

rdfs:label: Ear
dc:description: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance.

rdfs:label: Face
dc:description: The anterior portion of the head extending from the forehead to the chin and ear to ear. The facial structures contain the eyes, nose and mouth, cheeks and jaws.

rdfs:label: Face-part
dc:description: A part of the face.

rdfs:label: Cheek
dc:description: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jawline.

rdfs:label: Chin
dc:description: The part of the face below the lower lip and including the protruding part of the lower jaw.

rdfs:label: Eye
dc:description: The organ of sight or vision.

rdfs:label: Eyebrow
dc:description: The arched strip of hair on the bony ridge above each eye socket.

rdfs:label: Eyelid
dc:description: The folds of the skin that cover the eye when closed.

rdfs:label: Forehead
dc:description: The part of the face between the eyebrows and the normal hairline.

rdfs:label: Lip
dc:description: Fleshy fold which surrounds the opening of the mouth.

rdfs:label: Mouth
dc:description: The proximal portion of the digestive tract, containing the oral cavity and bounded by the oral opening.

rdfs:label: Mouth-part
dc:description: A part of the mouth.

rdfs:label: Teeth
dc:description: The hard bonelike structures in the jaws. A collection of teeth arranged in some pattern in the mouth or other part of the body.

rdfs:label: Tongue
dc:description: A muscular organ in the mouth with significant role in mastication, swallowing, speech, and taste.

rdfs:label: Nose
dc:description: A structure of special sense serving as an organ of the sense of smell and as an entrance to the respiratory tract.

rdfs:label: Hair
dc:description: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.

rdfs:label: Lower-extremity
dc:description: Refers to the whole inferior limb (leg and/or foot).

rdfs:label: Lower-extremity-part
dc:description: A part of the lower extremity.

rdfs:label: Ankle
dc:description: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

rdfs:label: Foot
dc:description: The structure found below the ankle joint required for locomotion.

rdfs:label: Foot-part
dc:description: A part of the foot.

rdfs:label: Heel
dc:description: The back of the foot below the ankle.

rdfs:label: Instep
dc:description: The part of the foot between the ball and the heel on the inner side.

rdfs:label: Toe
dc:description: A digit of the foot.

rdfs:label: Big-toe
dc:description: The largest toe on the inner side of the foot.

rdfs:label: Little-toe
dc:description: The smallest toe located on the outer side of the foot.

rdfs:label: Toes
dc:description: The terminal digits of the foot. Used to describe collective attributes of all toes, such as bending all toes

rdfs:label: Knee
dc:description: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia.

rdfs:label: Lower-leg
dc:description: The part of the leg between the knee and the ankle.

rdfs:label: Lower-leg-part
dc:description: A part of the lower leg.

rdfs:label: Calf
dc:description: The fleshy part at the back of the leg below the knee.

rdfs:label: Shin
dc:description: Front part of the leg below the knee.

rdfs:label: Upper-leg
dc:description: The part of the leg between the hip and the knee.

rdfs:label: Upper-leg-part
dc:description: A part of the upper leg.

rdfs:label: Thigh
dc:description: Upper part of the leg between hip and knee.

rdfs:label: Neck
dc:description: The part of the body connecting the head to the torso, containing the cervical spine and vital pathways of nerves, blood vessels, and the airway.

rdfs:label: Torso
dc:description: The body excluding the head and neck and limbs.

rdfs:label: Torso-part
dc:description: A part of the torso.

rdfs:label: Abdomen
dc:description: The part of the body between the thorax and the pelvis.

rdfs:label: Navel
dc:description: The central mark on the abdomen created by the detachment of the umbilical cord after birth.

rdfs:label: Pelvis
dc:description: The bony structure at the base of the spine supporting the legs.

rdfs:label: Pelvis-part
dc:description: A part of the pelvis.

rdfs:label: Buttocks
dc:description: The round fleshy parts that form the lower rear area of a human trunk.

rdfs:label: Genitalia
dc:description: The external organs of reproduction and urination, located in the pelvic region. This includes both male and female genital structures.

rdfs:label: Gentalia
dc:description: The external organs of reproduction. Deprecated due to spelling error. Use Genitalia.

rdfs:label: Hip
dc:description: The lateral prominence of the pelvis from the waist to the thigh.

rdfs:label: Torso-back
dc:description: The rear surface of the human body from the shoulders to the hips.

rdfs:label: Torso-chest
dc:description: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen.

rdfs:label: Viscera
dc:description: Internal organs of the body.

rdfs:label: Waist
dc:description: The abdominal circumference at the navel.

rdfs:label: Upper-extremity
dc:description: Refers to the whole superior limb (shoulder, arm, elbow, wrist, hand).

rdfs:label: Upper-extremity-part
dc:description: A part of the upper extremity.

rdfs:label: Elbow
dc:description: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

rdfs:label: Forearm
dc:description: Lower part of the arm between the elbow and wrist.

rdfs:label: Forearm-part
dc:description: A part of the forearm.

rdfs:label: Hand
dc:description: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

rdfs:label: Hand-part
dc:description: A part of the hand.

rdfs:label: Finger
dc:description: Any of the digits of the hand.

rdfs:label: Index-finger
dc:description: The second finger from the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb.

rdfs:label: Little-finger
dc:description: The fifth and smallest finger from the radial side of the hand.

rdfs:label: Middle-finger
dc:description: The middle or third finger from the radial side of the hand.

rdfs:label: Ring-finger
dc:description: The fourth finger from the radial side of the hand.

rdfs:label: Thumb
dc:description: The thick and short hand digit which is next to the index finger in humans.

rdfs:label: Fingers
dc:description: The terminal digits of the hand. Used to describe collective attributes of all fingers, such as bending all fingers

rdfs:label: Knuckles
dc:description: A part of a finger at a joint where the bone is near the surface, especially where the finger joins the hand.

rdfs:label: Palm
dc:description: The part of the inner surface of the hand that extends from the wrist to the bases of the fingers.

rdfs:label: Shoulder
dc:description: Joint attaching upper arm to trunk.

rdfs:label: Upper-arm
dc:description: Portion of arm between shoulder and elbow.

rdfs:label: Upper-arm-part
dc:description: A part of the upper arm.

rdfs:label: Wrist
dc:description: A joint between the distal end of the radius and the proximal row of carpal bones.

rdfs:label: Organism
dc:description: A living entity, more specifically a biological entity that consists of one or more cells and is capable of genomic replication (independently or not).

rdfs:label: Animal
dc:description: A living organism that has membranous cell walls, requires oxygen and organic foods, and is capable of voluntary movement.

rdfs:label: Human
dc:description: The bipedal primate mammal Homo sapiens.

rdfs:label: Plant
dc:description: Any living organism that typically synthesizes its food from inorganic substances and possesses cellulose cell walls.

rdfs:label: Language-item
dc:description: An entity related to a systematic means of communicating by the use of sounds, symbols, or gestures.

rdfs:label: Character
dc:description: A mark or symbol used in writing.

rdfs:label: Clause
dc:description: Aunit of grammatical organization next below the sentence in rank, usually consisting of a subject and predicate.

rdfs:label: Glyph
dc:description: A hieroglyphic character, symbol, or pictograph.

rdfs:label: Nonword
dc:description: An unpronounceable group of letters or speech sounds that is surrounded by white space when written, is not accepted as a word by native speakers.

rdfs:label: Paragraph
dc:description: A distinct section of a piece of writing, usually dealing with a single theme.

rdfs:label: Phoneme
dc:description: Any of the minimally distinct units of sound in a specified language that distinguish one word from another.

rdfs:label: Phrase
dc:description: A phrase is a group of words functioning as a single unit in the syntax of a sentence.

rdfs:label: Pseudoword
dc:description: A pronounceable group of letters or speech sounds that looks or sounds like a word but that is not accepted as such by native speakers.

rdfs:label: Sentence
dc:description: A set of words that is complete in itself, conveying a statement, question, exclamation, or command and typically containing an explicit or implied subject and a predicate containing a finite verb.

rdfs:label: Syllable
dc:description: A unit of pronunciation having a vowel or consonant sound, with or without surrounding consonants, forming the whole or a part of a word.

rdfs:label: Textblock
dc:description: A block of text.

rdfs:label: Word
dc:description: A single distinct meaningful element of speech or writing, used with others (or sometimes alone) to form a sentence and typically surrounded by white space when written or printed.

rdfs:label: Object
dc:description: Something perceptible by one or more of the senses, especially by vision or touch. A material thing.

rdfs:label: Geometric-object
dc:description: An object or a representation that has structure and topology in space.

rdfs:label: 2D-shape
dc:description: A planar, two-dimensional shape.

rdfs:label: Arrow
dc:description: A shape with a pointed end indicating direction.

rdfs:label: Clockface
dc:description: The dial face of a clock. A location identifier based on clockface numbering or anatomic subregion.

rdfs:label: Cross
dc:description: A figure or mark formed by two intersecting lines crossing at their midpoints.

rdfs:label: Dash
dc:description: A horizontal stroke in writing or printing to mark a pause or break in sense or to represent omitted letters or words.

rdfs:label: Ellipse
dc:description: A closed plane curve resulting from the intersection of a circular cone and a plane cutting completely through it, especially a plane not parallel to the base.

rdfs:label: Circle
dc:description: A ring-shaped structure with every point equidistant from the center.

rdfs:label: Rectangle
dc:description: A parallelogram with four right angles.

rdfs:label: Square
dc:description: A square is a special rectangle with four equal sides.

rdfs:label: Single-point
dc:description: A point is a geometric entity that is located in a zero-dimensional spatial region and whose position is defined by its coordinates in some coordinate system.

rdfs:label: Star
dc:description: A conventional or stylized representation of a star, typically one having five or more points.

rdfs:label: Triangle
dc:description: A three-sided polygon.

rdfs:label: 3D-shape
dc:description: A geometric three-dimensional shape.

rdfs:label: Box
dc:description: A square or rectangular vessel, usually made of cardboard or plastic.

rdfs:label: Cube
dc:description: A solid or semi-solid in the shape of a three dimensional square.

rdfs:label: Cone
dc:description: A shape whose base is a circle and whose sides taper up to a point.

rdfs:label: Cylinder
dc:description: A surface formed by circles of a given radius that are contained in a plane perpendicular to a given axis, whose centers align on the axis.

rdfs:label: Ellipsoid
dc:description: A closed plane curve resulting from the intersection of a circular cone and a plane cutting completely through it, especially a plane not parallel to the base.

rdfs:label: Sphere
dc:description: A solid or hollow three-dimensional object bounded by a closed surface such that every point on the surface is equidistant from the center.

rdfs:label: Pyramid
dc:description: A polyhedron of which one face is a polygon of any number of sides, and the other faces are triangles with a common vertex.

rdfs:label: Pattern
dc:description: An arrangement of objects, facts, behaviors, or other things which have scientific, mathematical, geometric, statistical, or other meaning.

rdfs:label: Dots
dc:description: A small round mark or spot.

rdfs:label: LED-pattern
dc:description: A pattern created by lighting selected members of a fixed light emitting diode array.

rdfs:label: Ingestible-object
dc:description: Something that can be taken into the body by the mouth for digestion or absorption.

rdfs:label: Man-made-object
dc:description: Something constructed by human means.

rdfs:label: Building
dc:description: A structure that has a roof and walls and stands more or less permanently in one place.

rdfs:label: Attic
dc:description: A room or a space immediately below the roof of a building.

rdfs:label: Basement
dc:description: The part of a building that is wholly or partly below ground level.

rdfs:label: Entrance
dc:description: The means or place of entry.

rdfs:label: Roof
dc:description: A roof is the covering on the uppermost part of a building which provides protection from animals and weather, notably rain, but also heat, wind and sunlight.

rdfs:label: Room
dc:description: An area within a building enclosed by walls and floor and ceiling.

rdfs:label: Clothing
dc:description: A covering designed to be worn on the body.

rdfs:label: Device
dc:description: An object contrived for a specific purpose.

rdfs:label: Assistive-device
dc:description: A device that help an individual accomplish a task.

rdfs:label: Glasses
dc:description: Frames with lenses worn in front of the eye for vision correction, eye protection, or protection from UV rays.

rdfs:label: Writing-device
dc:description: A device used for writing.

rdfs:label: Pen
dc:description: A common writing instrument used to apply ink to a surface for writing or drawing.

rdfs:label: Pencil
dc:description: An implement for writing or drawing that is constructed of a narrow solid pigment core in a protective casing that prevents the core from being broken or marking the hand.

rdfs:label: Computing-device
dc:description: An electronic device which take inputs and processes results from the inputs.

rdfs:label: Cellphone
dc:description: A telephone with access to a cellular radio system so it can be used over a wide area, without a physical connection to a network.

rdfs:label: Desktop-computer
dc:description: A computer suitable for use at an ordinary desk.

rdfs:label: Laptop-computer
dc:description: A computer that is portable and suitable for use while traveling.

rdfs:label: Tablet-computer
dc:description: A small portable computer that accepts input directly on to its screen rather than via a keyboard or mouse.

rdfs:label: Engine
dc:description: A motor is a machine designed to convert one or more forms of energy into mechanical energy.

rdfs:label: IO-device
dc:description: Hardware used by a human (or other system) to communicate with a computer.

rdfs:label: Input-device
dc:description: A piece of equipment used to provide data and control signals to an information processing system such as a computer or information appliance.

rdfs:label: Computer-mouse
dc:description: A hand-held pointing device that detects two-dimensional motion relative to a surface.

rdfs:label: Mouse-button
dc:description: An electric switch on a computer mouse which can be pressed or clicked to select or interact with an element of a graphical user interface.

rdfs:label: Scroll-wheel
dc:description: A scroll wheel or mouse wheel is a wheel used for scrolling made of hard plastic with a rubbery surface usually located between the left and right mouse buttons and is positioned perpendicular to the mouse surface.

rdfs:label: Joystick
dc:description: A control device that uses a movable handle to create two-axis input for a computer device.

rdfs:label: Keyboard
dc:description: A device consisting of mechanical keys that are pressed to create input to a computer.

rdfs:label: Keyboard-key
dc:description: A button on a keyboard usually representing letters, numbers, functions, or symbols.

rdfs:label: Keyboard-key-#
dc:description: Value of a keyboard key.

rdfs:label: Keypad
dc:description: A device consisting of keys, usually in a block arrangement, that provides limited input to a system.

rdfs:label: Keypad-key
dc:description: A key on a separate section of a computer keyboard that groups together numeric keys and those for mathematical or other special functions in an arrangement like that of a calculator.

rdfs:label: Keypad-key-#
dc:description: Value of keypad key.

rdfs:label: Microphone
dc:description: A device designed to convert sound to an electrical signal.

rdfs:label: Push-button
dc:description: A switch designed to be operated by pressing a button.

rdfs:label: Output-device
dc:description: Any piece of computer hardware equipment which converts information into human understandable form.

rdfs:label: Auditory-device
dc:description: A device designed to produce sound.

rdfs:label: Headphones
dc:description: An instrument that consists of a pair of small loudspeakers, or less commonly a single speaker, held close to ears and connected to a signal source such as an audio amplifier, radio, CD player or portable media player.

rdfs:label: Loudspeaker
dc:description: A device designed to convert electrical signals to sounds that can be heard.

rdfs:label: Display-device
dc:description: An output device for presentation of information in visual or tactile form the latter used for example in tactile electronic displays for blind people.

rdfs:label: Computer-screen
dc:description: An electronic device designed as a display or a physical device designed to be a protective meshwork.

rdfs:label: Screen-window
dc:description: A part of a computer screen that contains a display different from the rest of the screen. A window is a graphical control element consisting of a visual area containing some of the graphical user interface of the program it belongs to and is framed by a window decoration.

rdfs:label: Head-mounted-display
dc:description: An instrument that functions as a display device, worn on the head or as part of a helmet, that has a small display optic in front of one (monocular HMD) or each eye (binocular HMD).

rdfs:label: LED-display
dc:description: A LED display is a flat panel display that uses an array of light-emitting diodes as pixels for a video display.

rdfs:label: Recording-device
dc:description: A device that copies information in a signal into a persistent information bearer.

rdfs:label: EEG-recorder
dc:description: A device for recording electric currents in the brain using electrodes applied to the scalp, to the surface of the brain, or placed within the substance of the brain.

rdfs:label: EMG-recorder
dc:description: A device for recording electrical activity of muscles using electrodes on the body surface or within the muscular mass.

rdfs:label: File-storage
dc:description: A device for recording digital information to a permanent media.

rdfs:label: MEG-recorder
dc:description: A device for measuring the magnetic fields produced by electrical activity in the brain, usually conducted externally.

rdfs:label: Motion-capture
dc:description: A device for recording the movement of objects or people.

rdfs:label: Tape-recorder
dc:description: A device for recording and reproduction usually using magnetic tape for storage that can be saved and played back.

rdfs:label: Touchscreen
dc:description: A control component that operates an electronic device by pressing the display on the screen.

rdfs:label: Machine
dc:description: A human-made device that uses power to apply forces and control movement to perform an action.

rdfs:label: Measurement-device
dc:description: A device that measures something.

rdfs:label: Clock
dc:description: A device designed to indicate the time of day or to measure the time duration of an event or action.

rdfs:label: Robot
dc:description: A mechanical device that sometimes resembles a living animal and is capable of performing a variety of often complex human tasks on command or by being programmed in advance.

rdfs:label: Tool
dc:description: A component that is not part of a device but is designed to support its assembly or operation.

rdfs:label: Document
dc:description: A physical object, or electronic counterpart, that is characterized by containing writing which is meant to be human-readable.

rdfs:label: Book
dc:description: A volume made up of pages fastened along one edge and enclosed between protective covers.

rdfs:label: Letter
dc:description: A written message addressed to a person or organization.

rdfs:label: Note
dc:description: A brief written record.

rdfs:label: Notebook
dc:description: A book for notes or memoranda.

rdfs:label: Questionnaire
dc:description: A document consisting of questions and possibly responses, depending on whether it has been filled out.

rdfs:label: Furnishing
dc:description: Furniture, fittings, and other decorative accessories, such as curtains and carpets, for a house or room.

rdfs:label: Manufactured-material
dc:description: Substances created or extracted from raw materials.

rdfs:label: Ceramic
dc:description: A hard, brittle, heat-resistant and corrosion-resistant material made by shaping and then firing a nonmetallic mineral, such as clay, at a high temperature.

rdfs:label: Glass
dc:description: A brittle transparent solid with irregular atomic structure.

rdfs:label: Paper
dc:description: A thin sheet material produced by mechanically or chemically processing cellulose fibres derived from wood, rags, grasses or other vegetable sources in water.

rdfs:label: Plastic
dc:description: Various high-molecular-weight thermoplastic or thermosetting polymers that are capable of being molded, extruded, drawn, or otherwise shaped and then hardened into a form.

rdfs:label: Steel
dc:description: An alloy made up of iron with typically a few tenths of a percent of carbon to improve its strength and fracture resistance compared to iron.

rdfs:label: Media
dc:description: Media are audio/visual/audiovisual modes of communicating information for mass consumption.

rdfs:label: Media-clip
dc:description: A short segment of media.

rdfs:label: Audio-clip
dc:description: A short segment of audio.

rdfs:label: Audiovisual-clip
dc:description: A short media segment containing both audio and video.

rdfs:label: Video-clip
dc:description: A short segment of video.

rdfs:label: Visualization
dc:description: An planned process that creates images, diagrams or animations from the input data.

rdfs:label: Animation
dc:description: A form of graphical illustration that changes with time to give a sense of motion or represent dynamic changes in the portrayal.

rdfs:label: Art-installation
dc:description: A large-scale, mixed-media constructions, often designed for a specific place or for a temporary period of time.

rdfs:label: Braille
dc:description: A display using a system of raised dots that can be read with the fingers by people who are blind.

rdfs:label: Image
dc:description: Any record of an imaging event whether physical or electronic.

rdfs:label: Cartoon
dc:description: A type of illustration, sometimes animated, typically in a non-realistic or semi-realistic style. The specific meaning has evolved over time, but the modern usage usually refers to either an image or series of images intended for satire, caricature, or humor. A motion picture that relies on a sequence of illustrations for its animation.

rdfs:label: Drawing
dc:description: A representation of an object or outlining a figure, plan, or sketch by means of lines.

rdfs:label: Icon
dc:description: A sign (such as a word or graphic symbol) whose form suggests its meaning.

rdfs:label: Painting
dc:description: A work produced through the art of painting.

rdfs:label: Photograph
dc:description: An image recorded by a camera.

rdfs:label: Movie
dc:description: A sequence of images displayed in succession giving the illusion of continuous movement.

rdfs:label: Outline-visualization
dc:description: A visualization consisting of a line or set of lines enclosing or indicating the shape of an object in a sketch or diagram.

rdfs:label: Point-light-visualization
dc:description: A display in which action is depicted using a few points of light, often generated from discrete sensors in motion capture.

rdfs:label: Sculpture
dc:description: A two- or three-dimensional representative or abstract forms, especially by carving stone or wood or by casting metal or plaster.

rdfs:label: Stick-figure-visualization
dc:description: A drawing showing the head of a human being or animal as a circle and all other parts as straight lines.

rdfs:label: Navigational-object
dc:description: An object whose purpose is to assist directed movement from one location to another.

rdfs:label: Path
dc:description: A trodden way. A way or track laid down for walking or made by continual treading.

rdfs:label: Road
dc:description: An open way for the passage of vehicles, persons, or animals on land.

rdfs:label: Lane
dc:description: A defined path with physical dimensions through which an object or substance may traverse.

rdfs:label: Runway
dc:description: A paved strip of ground on a landing field for the landing and takeoff of aircraft.

rdfs:label: Vehicle
dc:description: A mobile machine which transports people or cargo.

rdfs:label: Aircraft
dc:description: A vehicle which is able to travel through air in an atmosphere.

rdfs:label: Bicycle
dc:description: A human-powered, pedal-driven, single-track vehicle, having two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other.

rdfs:label: Boat
dc:description: A watercraft of any size which is able to float or plane on water.

rdfs:label: Car
dc:description: A wheeled motor vehicle used primarily for the transportation of human passengers.

rdfs:label: Cart
dc:description: A cart is a vehicle which has two wheels and is designed to transport human passengers or cargo.

rdfs:label: Tractor
dc:description: A mobile machine specifically designed to deliver a high tractive effort at slow speeds, and mainly used for the purposes of hauling a trailer or machinery used in agriculture or construction.

rdfs:label: Train
dc:description: A connected line of railroad cars with or without a locomotive.

rdfs:label: Truck
dc:description: A motor vehicle which, as its primary function, transports cargo rather than human passengers.

rdfs:label: Natural-object
dc:description: Something that exists in or is produced by nature, and is not artificial or man-made.

rdfs:label: Mineral
dc:description: A solid, homogeneous, inorganic substance occurring in nature and having a definite chemical composition.

rdfs:label: Natural-feature
dc:description: A feature that occurs in nature. A prominent or identifiable aspect, region, or site of interest.

rdfs:label: Field
dc:description: An unbroken expanse as of ice or grassland.

rdfs:label: Hill
dc:description: A rounded elevation of limited extent rising above the surrounding land with local relief of less than 300m.

rdfs:label: Mountain
dc:description: A landform that extends above the surrounding terrain in a limited area.

rdfs:label: River
dc:description: A natural freshwater surface stream of considerable volume and a permanent or seasonal flow, moving in a definite channel toward a sea, lake, or another river.

rdfs:label: Waterfall
dc:description: A sudden descent of water over a step or ledge in the bed of a river.

rdfs:label: Sound
dc:description: Mechanical vibrations transmitted by an elastic medium. Something that can be heard.

rdfs:label: Environmental-sound
dc:description: Sounds occurring in the environment. An accumulation of noise pollution that occurs outside. This noise can be caused by transport, industrial, and recreational activities.

rdfs:label: Crowd-sound
dc:description: Noise produced by a mixture of sounds from a large group of people.

rdfs:label: Signal-noise
dc:description: Any part of a signal that is not the true or original signal but is introduced by the communication mechanism.

rdfs:label: Musical-sound
dc:description: Sound produced by continuous and regular vibrations, as opposed to noise.

rdfs:label: Instrument-sound
dc:description: Sound produced by a musical instrument.

rdfs:label: Tone
dc:description: A musical note, warble, or other sound used as a particular signal on a telephone or answering machine.

rdfs:label: Vocalized-sound
dc:description: Musical sound produced by vocal cords in a biological agent.

rdfs:label: Named-animal-sound
dc:description: A sound recognizable as being associated with particular animals.

rdfs:label: Barking
dc:description: Sharp explosive cries like sounds made by certain animals, especially a dog, fox, or seal.

rdfs:label: Bleating
dc:description: Wavering cries like sounds made by a sheep, goat, or calf.

rdfs:label: Chirping
dc:description: Short, sharp, high-pitched noises like sounds made by small birds or an insects.

rdfs:label: Crowing
dc:description: Loud shrill sounds characteristic of roosters.

rdfs:label: Growling
dc:description: Low guttural sounds like those that made in the throat by a hostile dog or other animal.

rdfs:label: Meowing
dc:description: Vocalizations like those made by as those cats. These sounds have diverse tones and are sometimes chattered, murmured or whispered. The purpose can be assertive.

rdfs:label: Mooing
dc:description: Deep vocal sounds like those made by a cow.

rdfs:label: Purring
dc:description: Low continuous vibratory sound such as those made by cats. The sound expresses contentment.

rdfs:label: Roaring
dc:description: Loud, deep, or harsh prolonged sounds such as those made by big cats and bears for long-distance communication and intimidation.

rdfs:label: Squawking
dc:description: Loud, harsh noises such as those made by geese.

rdfs:label: Named-object-sound
dc:description: A sound identifiable as coming from a particular type of object.

rdfs:label: Alarm-sound
dc:description: A loud signal often loud continuous ringing to alert people to a problem or condition that requires urgent attention.

rdfs:label: Beep
dc:description: A short, single tone, that is typically high-pitched and generally made by a computer or other machine.

rdfs:label: Buzz
dc:description: A persistent vibratory sound often made by a buzzer device and used to indicate something incorrect.

rdfs:label: Click
dc:description: The sound made by a mechanical cash register, often to designate a reward.

rdfs:label: Ding
dc:description: A short ringing sound such as that made by a bell, often to indicate a correct response or the expiration of time.

rdfs:label: Horn-blow
dc:description: A loud sound made by forcing air through a sound device that funnels air to create the sound, often used to sound an alert.

rdfs:label: Ka-ching
dc:description: The sound made by a mechanical cash register, often to designate a reward.

rdfs:label: Siren
dc:description: A loud, continuous sound often varying in frequency designed to indicate an emergency.

rdfs:label: Property
dc:description: Something that pertains to a thing. A characteristic of some entity. A quality or feature regarded as a characteristic or inherent part of someone or something. HED attributes are adjectives or adverbs.
omn:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema)
owm:EquivalentTo: HedTag and (extensionAllowed value true) and (inHedSchema some StandardSchema

rdfs:label: Agent-property
dc:description: Something that pertains to or describes an agent.

rdfs:label: Agent-state
dc:description: The state of the agent.

rdfs:label: Agent-cognitive-state
dc:description: The state of the cognitive processes or state of mind of the agent.

rdfs:label: Alert
dc:description: Condition of heightened watchfulness or preparation for action.

rdfs:label: Anesthetized
dc:description: Having lost sensation to pain or having senses dulled due to the effects of an anesthetic.

rdfs:label: Asleep
dc:description: Having entered a periodic, readily reversible state of reduced awareness and metabolic activity, usually accompanied by physical relaxation and brain activity.

rdfs:label: Attentive
dc:description: Concentrating and focusing mental energy on the task or surroundings.

rdfs:label: Awake
dc:description: In a non sleeping state.

rdfs:label: Brain-dead
dc:description: Characterized by the irreversible absence of cortical and brain stem functioning.

rdfs:label: Comatose
dc:description: In a state of profound unconsciousness associated with markedly depressed cerebral activity.

rdfs:label: Distracted
dc:description: Lacking in concentration because of being preoccupied.

rdfs:label: Drowsy
dc:description: In a state of near-sleep, a strong desire for sleep, or sleeping for unusually long periods.

rdfs:label: Intoxicated
dc:description: In a state with disturbed psychophysiological functions and responses as a result of administration or ingestion of a psychoactive substance.

rdfs:label: Locked-in
dc:description: In a state of complete paralysis of all voluntary muscles except for the ones that control the movements of the eyes.

rdfs:label: Passive
dc:description: Not responding or initiating an action in response to a stimulus.

rdfs:label: Resting
dc:description: A state in which the agent is not exhibiting any physical exertion.

rdfs:label: Vegetative
dc:description: A state of wakefulness and conscience, but (in contrast to coma) with involuntary opening of the eyes and movements (such as teeth grinding, yawning, or thrashing of the extremities).

rdfs:label: Agent-emotional-state
dc:description: The status of the general temperament and outlook of an agent.

rdfs:label: Angry
dc:description: Experiencing emotions characterized by marked annoyance or hostility.

rdfs:label: Aroused
dc:description: In a state reactive to stimuli leading to increased heart rate and blood pressure, sensory alertness, mobility and readiness to respond.

rdfs:label: Awed
dc:description: Filled with wonder. Feeling grand, sublime or powerful emotions characterized by a combination of joy, fear, admiration, reverence, and/or respect.

rdfs:label: Compassionate
dc:description: Feeling or showing sympathy and concern for others often evoked for a person who is in distress and associated with altruistic motivation.

rdfs:label: Content
dc:description: Feeling satisfaction with things as they are.

rdfs:label: Disgusted
dc:description: Feeling revulsion or profound disapproval aroused by something unpleasant or offensive.

rdfs:label: Emotionally-neutral
dc:description: Feeling neither satisfied nor dissatisfied.

rdfs:label: Empathetic
dc:description: Understanding and sharing the feelings of another. Being aware of, being sensitive to, and vicariously experiencing the feelings, thoughts, and experience of another.

rdfs:label: Excited
dc:description: Feeling great enthusiasm and eagerness.

rdfs:label: Fearful
dc:description: Feeling apprehension that one may be in danger.

rdfs:label: Frustrated
dc:description: Feeling annoyed as a result of being blocked, thwarted, disappointed or defeated.

rdfs:label: Grieving
dc:description: Feeling sorrow in response to loss, whether physical or abstract.

rdfs:label: Happy
dc:description: Feeling pleased and content.

rdfs:label: Jealous
dc:description: Feeling threatened by a rival in a relationship with another individual, in particular an intimate partner, usually involves feelings of threat, fear, suspicion, distrust, anxiety, anger, betrayal, and rejection.

rdfs:label: Joyful
dc:description: Feeling delight or intense happiness.

rdfs:label: Loving
dc:description: Feeling a strong positive emotion of affection and attraction.

rdfs:label: Relieved
dc:description: No longer feeling pain, distress,anxiety, or reassured.

rdfs:label: Sad
dc:description: Feeling grief or unhappiness.

rdfs:label: Stressed
dc:description: Experiencing mental or emotional strain or tension.

rdfs:label: Agent-physiological-state
dc:description: Having to do with the mechanical, physical, or biochemical function of an agent.

rdfs:label: Catamenial
dc:description: Related to menstruation.

rdfs:label: Fever
dc:description: Body temperature above the normal range.

rdfs:label: Healthy
dc:description: Having no significant health-related issues.

rdfs:label: Hungry
dc:description: Being in a state of craving or desiring food.
omn:EquivalentTo: Agent-physiological-state and (relatedTag some Sated) and (relatedTag some Thirsty)
owm:EquivalentTo: Agent-physiological-state and (relatedTag some Sated) and (relatedTag some Thirsty)

rdfs:label: Rested
dc:description: Feeling refreshed and relaxed.

rdfs:label: Sated
dc:description: Feeling full.

rdfs:label: Sick
dc:description: Being in a state of ill health, bodily malfunction, or discomfort.

rdfs:label: Thirsty
dc:description: Feeling a need to drink.

rdfs:label: Tired
dc:description: Feeling in need of sleep or rest.

rdfs:label: Agent-postural-state
dc:description: Pertaining to the position in which agent holds their body.

rdfs:label: Crouching
dc:description: Adopting a position where the knees are bent and the upper body is brought forward and down, sometimes to avoid detection or to defend oneself.

rdfs:label: Eyes-closed
dc:description: Keeping eyes closed with no blinking.

rdfs:label: Eyes-open
dc:description: Keeping eyes open with occasional blinking.

rdfs:label: Kneeling
dc:description: Positioned where one or both knees are on the ground.

rdfs:label: On-treadmill
dc:description: Ambulation on an exercise apparatus with an endless moving belt to support moving in place.

rdfs:label: Prone
dc:description: Positioned in a recumbent body position whereby the person lies on its stomach and faces downward.

rdfs:label: Seated-with-chin-rest
dc:description: Using a device that supports the chin and head.

rdfs:label: Sitting
dc:description: In a seated position.

rdfs:label: Standing
dc:description: Assuming or maintaining an erect upright position.

rdfs:label: Agent-task-role
dc:description: The function or part that is ascribed to an agent in performing the task.

rdfs:label: Experiment-actor
dc:description: An agent who plays a predetermined role to create the experiment scenario.

rdfs:label: Experiment-controller
dc:description: An agent exerting control over some aspect of the experiment.

rdfs:label: Experiment-participant
dc:description: Someone who takes part in an activity related to an experiment.

rdfs:label: Experimenter
dc:description: Person who is the owner of the experiment and has its responsibility.

rdfs:label: Agent-trait
dc:description: A genetically, environmentally, or socially determined characteristic of an agent.

rdfs:label: Age
dc:description: Length of time elapsed time since birth of the agent.

rdfs:label: Agent-experience-level
dc:description: Amount of skill or knowledge that the agent has as pertains to the task.

rdfs:label: Expert-level
dc:description: Having comprehensive and authoritative knowledge of or skill in a particular area related to the task.
omn:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Intermediate-experience-level) and (relatedTag some Novice-level)
owm:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Intermediate-experience-level) and (relatedTag some Novice-level)

rdfs:label: Intermediate-experience-level
dc:description: Having a moderate amount of knowledge or skill related to the task.
omn:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Expert-level) and (relatedTag some Novice-level)
owm:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Expert-level) and (relatedTag some Novice-level)

rdfs:label: Novice-level
dc:description: Being inexperienced in a field or situation related to the task.
omn:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Expert-level) and (relatedTag some Intermediate-experience-level)
owm:EquivalentTo: Agent-experience-level and (relatedTag some Expert-level) and (relatedTag some Intermediate-experience-level)

rdfs:label: Ethnicity
dc:description: Belong to a social group that has a common national or cultural tradition. Use with Label to avoid extension.

rdfs:label: Gender
dc:description: Characteristics that are socially constructed, including norms, behaviors, and roles based on sex.

rdfs:label: Handedness
dc:description: Individual preference for use of a hand, known as the dominant hand.

rdfs:label: Ambidextrous
dc:description: Having no overall dominance in the use of right or left hand or foot in the performance of tasks that require one hand or foot.

rdfs:label: Left-handed
dc:description: Preference for using the left hand or foot for tasks requiring the use of a single hand or foot.

rdfs:label: Right-handed
dc:description: Preference for using the right hand or foot for tasks requiring the use of a single hand or foot.

rdfs:label: Race
dc:description: Belonging to a group sharing physical or social qualities as defined within a specified society. Use with Label to avoid extension.

rdfs:label: Sex
dc:description: Physical properties or qualities by which male is distinguished from female.

rdfs:label: Female
dc:description: Biological sex of an individual with female sexual organs such ova.

rdfs:label: Intersex
dc:description: Having genitalia and/or secondary sexual characteristics of indeterminate sex.

rdfs:label: Male
dc:description: Biological sex of an individual with male sexual organs producing sperm.

rdfs:label: Other-sex
dc:description: A non-specific designation of sexual traits.

rdfs:label: Data-property
dc:description: Something that pertains to data or information.

rdfs:label: Data-artifact
dc:description: An anomalous, interfering, or distorting signal originating from a source other than the item being studied.

rdfs:label: Biological-artifact
dc:description: A data artifact arising from a biological entity being measured.

rdfs:label: Chewing-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from moving the jaw in a chewing motion.

rdfs:label: ECG-artifact
dc:description: An electrical artifact from the far-field potential from pulsation of the heart, time locked to QRS complex.

rdfs:label: EMG-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from muscle activity and myogenic potentials at the measurements site. In EEG, myogenic potentials are the most common artifacts. Frontalis and temporalis muscles (e.g. clenching of jaw muscles) are common causes. Generally, the potentials generated in the muscles are of shorter duration than those generated in the brain. The frequency components are usually beyond 30-50 Hz, and the bursts are arrhythmic.

rdfs:label: Eye-artifact
dc:description: Ocular movements and blinks can result in artifacts in different types of data. In electrophysiology data, these can result transients and offsets the signal.

rdfs:label: Eye-blink-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from eye blinking. In EEG, Fp1/Fp2 electrodes become electropositive with eye closure because the cornea is positively charged causing a negative deflection in Fp1/Fp2. If the eye blink is unilateral, consider prosthetic eye.

rdfs:label: Eye-movement-artifact
dc:description: Eye movements can cause artifacts on recordings. The charge of the eye can especially cause artifacts in electrophysiology data.

rdfs:label: Horizontal-eye-movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from moving eyes left-to-right and right-to-left. In EEG, there is an upward deflection in the Fp2-F8 derivation, when the eyes move to the right side. In this case F8 becomes more positive and therefore. When the eyes move to the left, F7 becomes more positive and there is an upward deflection in the Fp1-F7 derivation.

rdfs:label: Nystagmus-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from nystagmus (a vision condition in which the eyes make repetitive, uncontrolled movements).

rdfs:label: Slow-eye-movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifacts originating from slow, rolling eye-movements, seen during drowsiness.

rdfs:label: Vertical-eye-movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from moving eyes up and down. In EEG, this causes positive potentials (50-100 micro V) with bi-frontal distribution, maximum at Fp1 and Fp2, when the eyeball rotates upward. The downward rotation of the eyeball is associated with the negative deflection. The time course of the deflections is similar to the time course of the eyeball movement.

rdfs:label: Movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifact in the measured data generated by motion of the subject.

rdfs:label: Pulse-artifact
dc:description: A mechanical artifact from a pulsating blood vessel near a measurement site, cardioballistic artifact.

rdfs:label: Respiration-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from breathing.

rdfs:label: Rocking-patting-artifact
dc:description: Quasi-rhythmical artifacts in recordings most commonly seen in infants. Typically caused by a caregiver rocking or patting the infant.

rdfs:label: Sucking-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from sucking, typically seen in very young cases.

rdfs:label: Sweat-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from sweating. In EEG, this is a low amplitude undulating waveform that is usually greater than 2 seconds and may appear to be an unstable baseline.

rdfs:label: Tongue-movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from tongue movement (Glossokinetic). The tongue functions as a dipole, with the tip negative with respect to the base. In EEG, the artifact produced by the tongue has a broad potential field that drops from frontal to occipital areas, although it is less steep than that produced by eye movement artifacts. The amplitude of the potentials is greater inferiorly than in parasagittal regions; the frequency is variable but usually in the delta range. Chewing and sucking can produce similar artifacts.

rdfs:label: Nonbiological-artifact
dc:description: A data artifact arising from a non-biological source.

rdfs:label: Artificial-ventilation-artifact
dc:description: Artifact stemming from mechanical ventilation. These can occur at the same rate as the ventilator, but also have other patterns.

rdfs:label: Dialysis-artifact
dc:description: Artifacts seen in recordings during continuous renal replacement therapy (dialysis).

rdfs:label: Electrode-movement-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from electrode movement.

rdfs:label: Electrode-pops-artifact
dc:description: Brief artifact with a steep rise and slow fall of an electrophysiological signal, most often caused by a loose electrode.

rdfs:label: Induction-artifact
dc:description: Artifacts induced by nearby equipment. In EEG, these are usually of high frequency.

rdfs:label: Line-noise-artifact
dc:description: Power line noise at 50 Hz or 60 Hz.

rdfs:label: Line-noise-artifact-#
omn:EquivalentTo: Line-noise-artifact and (valueClass some numericClass) and (unitClass some frequencyUnits)
owm:EquivalentTo: Line-noise-artifact and (valueClass some numericClass) and (unitClass some frequencyUnits)

rdfs:label: Salt-bridge-artifact
dc:description: Artifact from salt-bridge between EEG electrodes.

rdfs:label: Data-marker
dc:description: An indicator placed to mark something.

rdfs:label: Data-break-marker
dc:description: An indicator place to indicate a gap in the data.

rdfs:label: Temporal-marker
dc:description: An indicator placed at a particular time in the data.

rdfs:label: Inset
dc:description: Marks an intermediate point in an ongoing event of temporal extent.
omn:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Onset) and (relatedTag some Offset)
owm:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Onset) and (relatedTag some Offset)

rdfs:label: Offset
dc:description: Marks the end of an event of temporal extent.
omn:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Onset) and (relatedTag some Inset)
owm:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Onset) and (relatedTag some Inset)

rdfs:label: Onset
dc:description: Marks the start of an ongoing event of temporal extent.
omn:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Inset) and (relatedTag some Offset)
owm:EquivalentTo: Temporal-marker and (topLevelTagGroup value true) and (reserved value true) and (relatedTag some Inset) and (relatedTag some Offset)

rdfs:label: Pause
dc:description: Indicates the temporary interruption of the operation of a process and subsequently a wait for a signal to continue.

rdfs:label: Time-out
dc:description: A cancellation or cessation that automatically occurs when a predefined interval of time has passed without a certain event occurring.

rdfs:label: Time-sync
dc:description: A synchronization signal whose purpose is to help synchronize different signals or processes. Often used to indicate a marker inserted into the recorded data to allow post hoc synchronization of concurrently recorded data streams.

rdfs:label: Data-resolution
dc:description: Smallest change in a quality being measured by an sensor that causes a perceptible change.

rdfs:label: Printer-resolution
dc:description: Resolution of a printer, usually expressed as the number of dots-per-inch for a printer.

rdfs:label: Screen-resolution
dc:description: Resolution of a screen, usually expressed as the of pixels in a dimension for a digital display device.

rdfs:label: Sensory-resolution
dc:description: Resolution of measurements by a sensing device.

rdfs:label: Spatial-resolution
dc:description: Linear spacing of a spatial measurement.

rdfs:label: Spectral-resolution
dc:description: Measures the ability of a sensor to resolve features in the electromagnetic spectrum.

rdfs:label: Temporal-resolution
dc:description: Measures the ability of a sensor to resolve features in time.

rdfs:label: Data-source-type
dc:description: The type of place, person, or thing from which the data comes or can be obtained.

rdfs:label: Computed-feature
dc:description: A feature computed from the data by a tool. This tag should be grouped with a label of the form Toolname_propertyName.

rdfs:label: Computed-prediction
dc:description: A computed extrapolation of known data.

rdfs:label: Expert-annotation
dc:description: An explanatory or critical comment or other in-context information provided by an authority.

rdfs:label: Instrument-measurement
dc:description: Information obtained from a device that is used to measure material properties or make other observations.

rdfs:label: Observation
dc:description: Active acquisition of information from a primary source. Should be grouped with a label of the form AgentID_featureName.

rdfs:label: Data-value
dc:description: Designation of the type of a data item.

rdfs:label: Categorical-value
dc:description: Indicates that something can take on a limited and usually fixed number of possible values.

rdfs:label: Categorical-class-value
dc:description: Categorical values that fall into discrete classes such as true or false. The grouping is absolute in the sense that it is the same for all participants.

rdfs:label: All
dc:description: To a complete degree or to the full or entire extent.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some Some) and (relatedTag some None)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some Some) and (relatedTag some None)

rdfs:label: Correct
dc:description: Free from error. Especially conforming to fact or truth.

rdfs:label: Explicit
dc:description: Stated clearly and in detail, leaving no room for confusion or doubt.

rdfs:label: False
dc:description: Not in accordance with facts, reality or definitive criteria.

rdfs:label: Implicit
dc:description: Implied though not plainly expressed.

rdfs:label: Invalid
dc:description: Not allowed or not conforming to the correct format or specifications.

rdfs:label: None
dc:description: No person or thing, nobody, not any.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some All) and (relatedTag some Some)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some All) and (relatedTag some Some)

rdfs:label: Some
dc:description: At least a small amount or number of, but not a large amount of, or often.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some All) and (relatedTag some None)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-class-value and (relatedTag some All) and (relatedTag some None)

rdfs:label: True
dc:description: Conforming to facts, reality or definitive criteria.

rdfs:label: Unknown
dc:description: The information has not been provided.

rdfs:label: Valid
dc:description: Allowable, usable, or acceptable.

rdfs:label: Wrong
dc:description: Inaccurate or not correct.

rdfs:label: Categorical-judgment-value
dc:description: Categorical values that are based on the judgment or perception of the participant such familiar and famous.

rdfs:label: Abnormal
dc:description: Deviating in any way from the state, position, structure, condition, behavior, or rule which is considered a norm.

rdfs:label: Asymmetrical
dc:description: Lacking symmetry or having parts that fail to correspond to one another in shape, size, or arrangement.

rdfs:label: Audible
dc:description: A sound that can be perceived by the participant.

rdfs:label: Complex
dc:description: Hard, involved or complicated, elaborate, having many parts.

rdfs:label: Congruent
dc:description: Concordance of multiple evidence lines. In agreement or harmony.

rdfs:label: Constrained
dc:description: Keeping something within particular limits or bounds.

rdfs:label: Disordered
dc:description: Not neatly arranged. Confused and untidy. A structural quality in which the parts of an object are non-rigid.

rdfs:label: Familiar
dc:description: Recognized, familiar, or within the scope of knowledge.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Unfamiliar) and (relatedTag some Famous)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Unfamiliar) and (relatedTag some Famous)

rdfs:label: Famous
dc:description: A person who has a high degree of recognition by the general population for his or her success or accomplishments. A famous person.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Familiar) and (relatedTag some Unfamiliar)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Familiar) and (relatedTag some Unfamiliar)

rdfs:label: Inaudible
dc:description: A sound below the threshold of perception of the participant.

rdfs:label: Incongruent
dc:description: Not in agreement or harmony.

rdfs:label: Involuntary
dc:description: An action that is not made by choice. In the body, involuntary actions (such as blushing) occur automatically, and cannot be controlled by choice.

rdfs:label: Masked
dc:description: Information exists but is not provided or is partially obscured due to security,privacy, or other concerns.

rdfs:label: Normal
dc:description: Being approximately average or within certain limits. Conforming with or constituting a norm or standard or level or type or social norm.

rdfs:label: Ordered
dc:description: Conforming to a logical or comprehensible arrangement of separate elements.

rdfs:label: Simple
dc:description: Easily understood or presenting no difficulties.

rdfs:label: Symmetrical
dc:description: Made up of exactly similar parts facing each other or around an axis. Showing aspects of symmetry.

rdfs:label: Unconstrained
dc:description: Moving without restriction.

rdfs:label: Unfamiliar
dc:description: Not having knowledge or experience of.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Familiar) and (relatedTag some Famous)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-judgment-value and (relatedTag some Familiar) and (relatedTag some Famous)

rdfs:label: Unmasked
dc:description: Information is revealed.

rdfs:label: Voluntary
dc:description: Using free will or design; not forced or compelled; controlled by individual volition.

rdfs:label: Categorical-level-value
dc:description: Categorical values based on dividing a continuous variable into levels such as high and low.

rdfs:label: Cold
dc:description: Having an absence of heat.

rdfs:label: Deep
dc:description: Extending relatively far inward or downward.

rdfs:label: High
dc:description: Having a greater than normal degree, intensity, or amount.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Low) and (relatedTag some Medium)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Low) and (relatedTag some Medium)

rdfs:label: Hot
dc:description: Having an excess of heat.

rdfs:label: Large
dc:description: Having a great extent such as in physical dimensions, period of time, amplitude or frequency.

rdfs:label: Liminal
dc:description: Situated at a sensory threshold that is barely perceptible or capable of eliciting a response.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Subliminal) and (relatedTag some Supraliminal)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Subliminal) and (relatedTag some Supraliminal)

rdfs:label: Loud
dc:description: Having a perceived high intensity of sound.

rdfs:label: Low
dc:description: Less than normal in degree, intensity or amount.

rdfs:label: Medium
dc:description: Mid-way between small and large in number, quantity, magnitude or extent.
omn:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Low) and (relatedTag some High)
owm:EquivalentTo: Categorical-level-value and (relatedTag some Low) and (relatedTag some High)

rdfs:label: Negative
dc:description: Involving disadvantage or harm.

rdfs:label: Positive
dc:description: Involving advantage or good.

rdfs:label: Quiet
dc:description: Characterizing a perceived low intensity of sound.

rdfs:label: Rough
dc:description: Having a surface with perceptible bumps, ridges, or irregularities.

rdfs:label: Shallow
dc:description: Having a depth which is relatively low.

rdfs:label: Small
